Longer than his finger ring finger means lower cancer risk
Men, who have the index finger longer than your ring finger, are exposed to decreased the risk that become ill prostate cancer.
It is surprising conclusion Cancer Study, which on Wednesday published a British magazine.
It may be related to the surface of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative finger length can serve as a simple test risk of prostate cancer, particularly for a man to 60 years," she said spoluautorka studies Ros eelesová, Professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Finger so could help determine who men should Take test for prostate cancer, in particular in combination with a genetic risk factors or other threats, such as family health burden, she added eelesová.
In the period 1994-2009 followed with colleagues in Britain, more than 1,500 patients over three thousands of healthy men with prostate cancer, and in parallel.
More than half of the participants in the study had his finger on his right hand shorter than the ring finger.
It paid for them the same likelihood of prostate cancer, as for 19 percent of those whose fingers were of the same length.
In the case of those who had his finger longer than your ring finger, but this risk decreased to about 33 percent, for a man to age sixty, decline even 87 percent.
The ratio of these two fingers - shaped by in prenatal - probably reflects the different levels of child sex hormones, which are on display in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer forefinger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone supports the growing prostate cancer.
The Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences Professor Wenceslas pačes for čtk said that knows about this study subjects, but he said that should the relationship between the length of fingerprints and cancer was "completely proven."
