Common practice of democracy
The promotion of democracy in Latin America is growing, as well as the promotion of private business.
Crime is of greater concern than unemployment.
Many regions as more influential than the United States and Brazil.
These are some of the results of the survey latinobarómetro, which took place in 18 countries and went exclusively in the magazine The Economist.
Since the survey held regularly since 1995, so can track changes in their attitudes across the whole area.
In this year's survey, which was held in September and at the beginning of October, is dominated by two related things.
The first of them is that Latin America is quite a happy mood.
The second is to enhance stability attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
The promotion of democracy in several countries on the fringe of the Pacific has risen significantly in South America, see Table 1.
In Peru, where, for example, is from a 2002 economic growth in average of 6 percent per year, increased support for Democracy of minimum 40% in the year 2005 to 61% in the current year.
Rose also in Mexico, where the economics convalescent after deep decline in production in the last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous areas are believed Democrats, which brings the regional average, see chart 2.
About 44% of the respondents across the areas cited satisfaction with how democracy works in their country in practice, this is about the same number as in the last year, but in comparison with the year of 2001, when it was about 25%, this is a big increase in the chart 3."
Some 34% said that they trust the Assembly, in their own country and 45% of the trusted by the government, once again, this is about the same number as in the past year, but this is a big difference in comparison with the year 2003, 17% and 24%.
Ten years ago undermined democracy in Latin America, the economic crisis.
Support was established during the world financial crisis, probably for that reason, that many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and enjoyed strong recovery.
In addition, stronger network of social security help to protect the poor people.
The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America, announced this week that the ratio of Hispanic living in poverty has increased in the year 2009 only slightly, and again in this year fell to 32%.
But mood change in a wide range of from country to country, see chart 4.
Brazil's strong economic performance and its popularity of outgoing President Luis Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widely acclaimed sense of progress.
This situation is rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was serious and aggravated the situation of violent crime.
For only the second time since they came to carry out surveys, sees more respondents across Latin America as the most important problem crime rather than unemployment, see chart 5,.
Roughly 31% says that either they or their close relatives have become the victims of crime in the last year, but this is a decrease in comparison with by 38% of last year, and it is also the lowest number since 1995.
Masivnější economic performance is reflected in the growing support for private business and market economy: around 71% of the respondents across the area says that private business, it is necessary for development, this percentage has increased from 56% of the year 2007, see chart 6.
About 58% agree with that, that the market economy is the only system that will allow the development of their country, this percentage has increased from 47% of the last year.
Interesting is that 62% of the respondents in Venezuela has the same opinion, and 80% supports private business there, although their leftist president Hugo Chavez vyvlastňuje, many private companies.
Brazil is the country which has a leading position in the field, as have mentioned the 19% of the respondents, compared to 18 percent in last year, followed by the United States, 9%, unchanged from last year, and Venezuela, 9% compared to 11% in the last year.
However, the United States are considered to be the most influential country respondents in Mexico and in much of Central America, while Venezuela has enjoyed success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
