Veterans of the Red khmérů are forced to deal with the past
In a dimly lighted a concrete room with zašpiněnými and oloupanými walls reminded school director anlong veng High School of the man who built it, the Khmer Rouge leader the drink.
"All love the moka here."
"He was a good leader and took care of his people," he said sreng kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, during the government of Khmer Rouge atrocities, the Khmer Rouge commander in this remote estate in northwest Cambodia remains popular, where built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure still lives and where thousands of former soldiers of this organization.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge gave up the government, she's busted prolonged loyalty also in anlong vengu.
In April was the victims in the forum of Truth and Reconciliation to publicly confront with the people, who were part of the regime.
In June, the government has provided textbooks, which for the first time children explain the history of Khmer Rouge leaders and their former soldiers.
And in July to the UN and Cambodia's court together the first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge leaders, a conviction of former leader, notoriously known of a violent associations tuol sleng, kaing khek iev, známějšího as spirit, to 35 years in prison.
With every such progress, rising unrest among veterans of the Khmer Rouge in the anlong veng, which complicates efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to participate in the Cambodian society again.
"between the former Khmer khmery is resentment and fear, but they are powerless to do anything," he said chhang youk, director of the Documentation Center of Cambodia, an independent organization that examines the regime.
"For them, life was between the red khmery beautiful, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"It divides families."
During the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or to reprocessing.
When the Vietnamese attacked and overthrew the government of Pol Pot in 1979, the remnants of the regime and his soldiers fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There launched the insurgency, which lasted until the last movement in December 1998.
Pol Pot, Nuon chea and Ieng Sary followed guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles in Western Cambodia, while the drink, kultivoval supporters in anlong vengu.
But in the 1990s, following the peace agreement, sponsored by the UN, the country was conducted for the first democratic elections in 1993. A large group of fighters of Khmer Rouge leaders began to move to the Government, which culminated in the surrender Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon chea and Khieu samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes, continues in 1998 and the drink, which was captured by government forces in the nedalých mountains dangrek in 1999.
He died in Phnom penhském prison in 2006 while waiting for trial.
Their patrons have already nepečovali, most of them former combatants Khmer Rouge sank in the plain of Cambodia's rural life, and many of them nostalgically recalls for movement.
Although a number of elite Khmer Rouge to retain its position as local government in exchange for their weapons, their position remains weak, as unskilled farmers.
"These people should benefit from the surrender only the minimum," said rival leang from the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which leads public forum across Cambodia, including anlong vengu.
"They are surrounded by utopickou agricultural ideology of the regime."
"They were bedside manner without any ideas on the implementation of the trade."
Sor Lim, 55, who came to the khmerům as a teenager in 1974, and fought in the jungle around anlong vengu before he as a poor farmer in the year 1998.
"life under the Khmer khmery was good," he said.
"The drink, all sustenance."
"But now is a hard life, because we all must ensure themselves."
Ongoing court of Khmer Rouge leaders also provoked concerns.
At the beginning of next year to court to investigate Nuon chea, Khieu samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng thirith, another former Minister of Khmer Rouge atrocities.
The Court has a mandate to prosecute the přestavitele and people responsible for the crimes, but has not said whether it will continue also in the four of the cases.
It was only a little, to have been reassured concerns in anlong vengu.
Recent media speculation focused on the IM chaema, 64, who was a regional leader in the province banteay meanchey during the reign of the Khmer Rouge in the late 1970s.
In the year 2007, said the researchers from the Documentation Center of Cambodia, that supervised the construction of dams trapeang thma project, which probably killed thousands of forced workers.
Recent smoking evening IM chaem back from work in the field to its wooden cottage on dirty way out of anlong veng.
As the sun began to walk and explore the shadows over dry grass, im chaem refused to talk about their past the Red khmery.
If it wants to see her Court rejected would go.
"In Cambodia, of peace and it is stable," she said.
"If will be another criminal prosecution, there's going to be a war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, which he defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, also repeatedly warned that it comes to instability if the court searches for other suspects, although experts and historians do not agree with it.
"Cambodia must dig deep hole and bury the past in it," he said.
But confrontation with the past is just what Cambodia has to do to move forward, he said chhang youk from the Documentation Center.
"reconciliation in khmerským circumstances of the means slepení shattered pieces," he said.
"It is our duty to give the broken pieces together, we can understand."
Center, first approved by the Government on the red khmerech, has 75 of the parties and the name of the book "The history of democratic Cambodia."
Was distributed in anlong vengu in June as a supplement to the history book of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four parties of the Red khmerech.
As well as many people in Cambodia, also of young people in anlong vengu knew only few details about the khmerech, despite the city with the regime.
Touch valeak, 19, a student at the high school in anlong veng said that the new book helps students understand the important part of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically, when he took home the book to study.
"My family refuses to many parts of the book and the courts," he said.
"There are suspicious, because they are not sure how many people will be court to prosecute."
A resistance is reconciliation process more complex and more difficult, said rival leang.
But public forum, textbooks and the Court is beginning to have an impact, said further.
The Khmer Rouge here are still strong spell.
Up in the mountains dangrek mountains is the overgrown weeds and vysypaná odhozenými plastic bags, which leads to a rectangle of black soot, covered rusty tin roof.
The body, Pol pota here was burned on a pile of tyres after his death in 1998.
Nuom sothea, 31, cell phones on the edge of a road, said she doesn't know a lot about the man, who was at the place cremated.
"But it has a strong spirit, many local people come through here and praying for him," she said.
Nuom sothea should birthday and in the plan later to visit the place where rest Pol pota, will bring a ripe bananas, in the hope that it will bring luck.
Belarus agrees that it seems their stocks of weapons on the basis of uranium
In DID with its surprise victory in the campaign of President Obama on ensuring the nuclear material around the world, the Belarusian Government announced on Wednesday that give up their stocks of highly enriched uranium, which is a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The agreement was published in a joint statement, issued after the security summit Secretary Hillary rodham Clinton and Belarusian Foreign Minister by Sergei Martynov.
US government have for years sought to persuade Belarus to relinquishing the highly enriched uranium, and it seemed that the stumbling block discovered last spring.
But US officials have told the Washington Post, that in the past two months with Belarus was carried out a couple of clandestine operations to eliminate 187 pounds of weapons on the basis of uranium from the Belarusian research facilities.
That set the stage for Wednesday an agreement for the removal of the rest of the material - about 500 pounds, according to the official, who spoke on condition anonymity because it is a sensitive matter.
Agreement has turned out to be one of the most important results of Obama's 47th national summit on nuclear security in April, on which the Belarus was taken off the list.
And was probably a good move to ensure the invitation of the former Soviet republic to the subsequent summit in the year 2012.
"I was really fascinated with the fact that they want to place on the summit on nuclear bezpečnosti2012."
"It shows that the process works," said Ken luongo, president of the Partnership for global security, a group supporting nuclear safety.
Clinton called the agreement as "very important, an important step" from Belarus.
Obama said in Prague in April 2009, that will ensure all sensitive nuclear materials around the world to four years.
Since then, the US government helped six countries to get rid of all of its stocks of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will be the seventh.
A dozen countries have done so for the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of Obama's summit on nuclear security, a Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko said that his nation will never surrender its uranium.
"We have a highly enriched uranium - hundreds of kilograms of what is in the essence of the basis for a weapon and less enriched uranium," he said after Lukashenko.
"It is our commodity... we are not going to produce a dirty bombs and also we are not going to sell it."
"We use it only for research purposes, that's all."
Belarus, however, several months ago acceded to the United States and it expressed interest in reaching an agreement.
The first commitment to eliminate the Belarusian uranium in October, he was particularly difficult, because the material was slightly ozářen, officials announced.
Was loaded on a special train, which traveled more than 1, 300 miles in the Russian equipment for the storage and disposal, officials said.
The second operation was closed on Monday and was carried out by air, officials said.
The US government for the programme spent 13 million dollars, most of it for the supply of the research institute less enriched uranium, which is for the production of nuclear weapons a statesman.
"Everything was zkoordinováno very carefully and conducted on the basis of confidence," which led to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew bieniawski, an official of the Ministry of Energy workers for the Global Threat Reduction.
James Martin Center for the Study of the non nuclear weapons, this year estimated that Belarus has at least 88 pounds of uranium applicable for production of weapons.
Belarus will, according to the joint statement, to remove its stocks by the year 2012.
Tense relations between Belarus and the United States have been over the years, and it mainly because of lukašenkově a brutal repression of human rights.
But Wednesday statement suggests the possibility of gradual thaw.
"We welcome the progress in the global security issues, the United States and Belarus to acknowledge that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains the basis of improve mutual relations and it is necessary for the progress of the country and its people," he said.
