China respects its goal of reducing greenhouse gases
The country's representative at the United Nations Conference on Climate Change cop16 assured that his country has made every effort to reduce the carbon tracks, and ruled that insists on its promise reduced by the year 2020 greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45%.
China will keep its promise to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45% in the year 2020, said Su Wei, the country's representative at the United Nations conference on climate change.
In his first public statement on the 16th Conference of the Parties to the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, Su Wei assured that his country has made huge efforts to reduced carbon footprint and renamed its industry.
He said that his country during the last four years has already invested $245 million in the efforts to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases.
Ozřejmil, however, that China its objectives of change, and will continue to work together with the international community on this matter.
Reported that China's strategy in matters of climate change are distributed on the four items: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programs.
In all these points have already seen progress, which include the approval of a new law on energy, which includes the proposed targets for reducing emissions of greenhouse gases, he explained.
Further pointed out that in China cooperated with federal authorities in a coordinated manner with provincial and local authorities to achieve their goals, if it is about saving energy efficient use of energy and the reduction of emissions.
Further, as said, are in operation or have already been completed the various years plans, which are financed by the Chinese government, as well as other State governments.
For example, he said, it is a programme for the efficient use of energy, which was introduced in the last five years, and who received investment from the United Nations, governments and private initiatives.
Also running Provincial Project of climate change, as well as the exchange of bulbs for efficient light bulbs and Mitigation Project project and adaptation, he said.
